Fix: Reward data normalization, quantile sampling, and allocation config

Three correctness bugs were found and fixed in the reward model preference
pair data pipeline, and the allocation logic was redesigned to give
explicit control over data composition.

--- Bug Fixes ---

1. rJokes score normalization cap was set to 20, but the actual maximum
   raw score in the dataset is 11. The cap was never triggered, causing
   the effective range to be [0, 0.55] instead of [0, 1]. Fixed by
   changing RJOKES_SCORE_CAP from 20 to 11 in parsers.py.

2. Score-based quantile split in format_reward_pairs() used ">= q70" and
   "<= q30" thresholds. All three datasets have highly discrete scores
   (rJokes: 12 unique values, Chinese Humor: 5 unique values, HAHA: 61%
   at score=0), causing entire tie groups to be included and violating
   the intended 30/40/30 split. For example, rJokes was selecting 75% of
   data instead of 60%. Fixed by using rank-based selection with random
   tie-breaking: indices are shuffled then stable-sorted by score, and
   exactly the bottom/top 30% by index position are taken.

3. synthesize_reward_data.py score threshold for EN was 0.25, calibrated
   for the old cap of 20 (= raw >= 5). After changing cap to 11, the
   threshold was updated to round(5/11, 4) = 0.4545 to select the same
   raw score >= 5 pool.

--- Redesign: allocation config replaces max_pairs_per_lang ---

The original max_pairs_per_lang parameter was a single cap applied after
merging score-based and synthesized pairs, which could not control the
composition ratio between the two types. Analysis of the pre-fix dataset
showed:
  EN: 5.3% hard-negative, 94.7% score-based
  ES: 40.7% hard-negative, 59.3% score-based
  ZH: 92.5% hard-negative, 7.5% score-based

This imbalance meant EN/ES models lacked signals to score boring text
low, which was the root cause of observed language bias (boring English
text scoring 0.2–0.6, while boring Chinese text scored ~0.98 in the
pre-fix model).

Replaced max_pairs_per_lang with REWARD_PAIR_ALLOCATION constant in
formatters.py, which independently caps score_based and synthesized
counts per language:
  EN: score_based=7000, synthesized=7000  → 50% hard-negative
  ES: score_based=7000, synthesized=7000  → 50% hard-negative
  ZH: score_based=None (all ~1230),       → ~91% hard-negative
      synthesized=13000

--- Instrumentation ---

format_reward_pairs() now prints a composition table at the end of
Step 4, showing score_based / synthesized / total per language.

--- Data Visualization Updates ---

visulization.ipynb received three improvements:
  - Added Unified Dataset Score Statistics section (cells 2-3):
    loads unified_all.jsonl, prints per-source stats at key thresholds
    (0.25, 0.30, 0.50, 0.70), and renders histogram + box-plot.
  - Added HAHA 2019 dataset statistics section (cells 9-13):
    mirrors the existing rJokes analysis with is_humor distribution,
    funniness score histograms, text length distribution, and top/bottom
    samples.
  - Replaced regex-based detect_lang() in the Rebalanced Preference
    Pairs Overview section with langid-based detection
    (langid.set_languages + langid.classify), using prompt+chosen text
    for better classification accuracy.

